<org.eclipse.epf.uma:ProcessDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmi:id="-92zXLVOXI7ZzQ_L2hmw8dw" name="Service Specification Architecture,_3lNiMcXXEd2mI92i3AfRmg" guid="-92zXLVOXI7ZzQ_L2hmw8dw">
  <mainDescription>The services specification architecture acts as the ‘placeholder’ architecture. It defines the optimal (abstract) services&#xD;
descriptions aligned to the business requirements and fulfils the needs of a strategic direction for architecture.</mainDescription>
  <purpose>&lt;p style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;>&#xD;
    This process defines how to specify what kind of services will be needed to cover all the functionalities of the&#xD;
    system. These services will be part of the composition and the specifications will be used to find services which can&#xD;
    fulfil the requirements. All the specifications together will guarantee that the business process will meet the&#xD;
    original requirements.&#xD;
&lt;/p></purpose>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:ProcessDescription>
